#### 2.2 - Assessing Model Accuracy
- *There is no free lunch in statistics*, there is no one best method that dominates on all datasets

##### 2.2.1 - Measuring the quality of fit
- most commonly-used measure : ==Mean square error== (MSE)
- Generally we not really care about the *training MSE* (calculated on the training dataset), but more on **unseen test data** MSE
- We want to choose method that gives the lowest *test MSE*
- See image on the different methods' flexibility (***linear regression*** (2 dof) & two ***smoothing splines*** with different levels of "flexibility")
	- **degree of freedom** is a quantity that summarize the flexibility (-> see **Chapter 7**)
![Pasted image 20220410153507.png|500](data:image/png;base64,)
- the horizontal dashed line is the $Var(\epsilon)$ : the **irreducible error** (-> see **2.3**), which corresponds to the ==lowest achievable test MSE among all possible methods==, because of random error in the model
- As a model's flexibility increases, training MSE will decrease, but the test MSE may not (==--> overfitting the data==). ==> **U-shaped** curve => too flexible model
- see also other examples : images 2.10 & 2.11
- see method : *==Cross validation==* (-> see **Chapter 5**) to estimate test MSE from training data
